==English==
===Pronunciation===
*nēp, /niːp/, /<tt>ni:p</tt>/
*:[[Rhymes:English:-iːp|Rhymes: -iːp]]

===Etymology 1===
Perhaps of Scandinavian origin: compare dialectal Norwegian [[neip]] ‘forked pole’.

====Noun====
'''neap'''

#The [[tongue]] or [[pole]] of a cart or other vehicle drawn by two animals.

===Etymology 2===
Old English ''nēp'' in [[nepflod|nēpflōd]].

====Adjective====
{{en-ad2|'''neap'''|'''neaper'''|'''neapest'''}}
# designationg a [[tide]] which occurs just after the first and third quarters of the [[moon]], when there is least difference between high tide and low tide.
#:*'''1934''': Little groups of sailors came swinging along and pushied their way noisily inside the gaudy joints.  Sex everywhere: it was slopping over, a '''neap''' tide that swept the props from under the city. — Henry Miller, ''Tropic of Cancer''

